Title: [ERLLM-9] Observability - LLM usage costs
Description:
See Doc: https://www.notion.so/xapien/LLM-Observability-13d1edcf1daa80ff9462fec884d33255

Currently, we only have brief napkin maths on the estimated costs associated with LLM api calls. This can be found here: 

https://www.notion.so/xapien/LLM-Napkin-Maths-1351edcf1daa807b9414cfa134ff8338

We want to get observability of both throughput and cost for our services. We would like to ensure we have access to the following:


	For a given enquiry, how much did we spend on our various LLM api calls?
	For each service, how much do we typically spend on our LLM api calls?
	What is our given throughput for each service?



To do this, we expect we will need to:


	Track the number of input and output tokens for each prompt
	Work with the MLB code to implement. We will pass a client reference in the MLB requests to ensure we can track back to both the enquiry being run, and the service being hit.
	Ensure this is accessible via a dashboard, or some other observability interface. It should be easy to see for an enquiry (a) how much was spent and (b) where it was spent.
	
		Should be quick and easy enough for Joseph Whiting  to be able to access directly
		Communicate how to use it with Joseph Whiting and Jonah Ramoni

Title: [ERLLM-77] DEFUNCT: head selection for XI Corefs
Description:
We suspect that the current coref head selection code will be un-sufficient. The importance of head selection is twofold:


	The head must be interpretable, so that the GPT model can understand the chunks (the original goal of corefs)
	The head should look good for the user - we donâ€™t want to present chunks on screen with chunks that donâ€™t look right. This would represent a degradation in quality from the Fluenci solution.



To tackle this, we have a number of approaches:




	Something GPT based. This is my (Jonah's) favourite approach. This was Juanâ€™s idea, and in my testing it looks like GPT should be very good at head selection. The disadvantage of this is the cost. So perhaps some initial criteria to select when we make a GPT call for head selection. For instance, if too high a % of a mentionâ€™s words are not proper nouns.
	Something hacky. Like I had tried with the reselection mentions, we could try logic based on number of proper nouns or entities. The problem with this is that many of the coref clusters we get arenâ€™t necessarily about things that are identified as entities. For instance â€˜the meeting ran by Jonah Ramponiâ€™. I havenâ€™t been able to a way (other than GPT) of cleaning this one up - since entity / proper noun approaches would likely just leave us with â€˜Jonah Ramponiâ€™.






	This actually isnâ€™t a problem. I think the final approach is to hope that in cases where the output head was not good enough, there was a better head to select. Thus, the third approach would be to look at picking a better head from the candidates (if we identify that there is actually a problem here)

Title: [ERLLM-48] New corefs in production XI
Description:
As a Xapien user reading the Xapien Insights section, I hate it when it hallucinates! It really undermines my trust in Xapien as a system that I can rely on for my job.

One of the main ways â€œhallucinationsâ€ are generated is when we use incorrect corefs in our RAG pipeline - coming from the Fluenci corefs.

We have a new FCoref approach and coref service which we think is much more accurate (from testing by Jonah Ramoni). Weâ€™re already implementing that for use in ER reports, but weâ€™d like to benefit from the better accuracy in all reports.

Therefore the plan is to swap in the new corefs. Weâ€™ll route them to XI via https://digital-insight.atlassian.net/browse/ERIN-92. Weâ€™ll have to ensure that all the FDocs get sent for extraction and storage.

Coref related bugs here: https://digital-insight.atlassian.net/browse/ERLLM-40 

A side benefit of this is that it decouples XI from Fluenci, helping us move towards retiring it and saving us money on our AWS bill
